  "common_questions": [
    {
      "q": "What is CronAlarm?",
      "a": "A bash wrapper for cron jobs that alerts you the moment a job fails or hangs. Multi-channel (Discord, SMS, Telegram, local file). One-command install. No daemon, no server, just a wrapper script + log directory."
    },
    {
      "q": "Why not just use cron's native MAILTO?",
      "a": "MAILTO requires a working MTA and a mailbox someone actually checks. CronAlarm pings the channels you actually read — Discord, SMS, Telegram — and writes a permanent local report regardless. It also catches hangs, which MAILTO can't (a job that runs forever never emails)."
    },
    {
      "q": "What happens if a job hangs forever?",
      "a": "CronAlarm enforces a per-job timeout (CRONALARM_TIMEOUT, default 300 seconds). When the timeout is exceeded, the wrapper sends SIGKILL and fires an alert with the job name, hostname, and how long it ran before being killed. The job's output up to that point is captured to the log."
    },
    {
      "q": "Do I need a server / daemon / database?",
      "a": "No. CronAlarm is pure bash. The wrapper writes to local log files and posts to your configured channels via curl. No process needs to be running between cron jobs. Stops being 'installed' the moment you delete the scripts."
    },
    {
      "q": "Which notification channels are supported?",
      "a": "Four: Discord webhook (recommended), SMS via Textbelt (free tier = 1/day, paid tier ~$0.01/text), Telegram bot, and local file drop (~/.cronalarm/inbox/). Local file drop is always on so you have a permanent record even if a channel fails. Configure any subset; the script handles missing channels gracefully."
    },
    {
      "q": "How do I wrap an existing cron job?",
      "a": "Edit your crontab and prefix the command: `0 3 * * * cronalarm \"Hourly Backup\" /home/you/scripts/backup.sh`. The job runs normally; CronAlarm captures the output and alerts on failure or timeout. No changes needed inside your script."
    },
    {
      "q": "What does the daily summary look like?",
      "a": "Runs at 11 PM by default (configured by install.sh). Reads ~/.cronalarm/logs/YYYY-MM-DD.log, counts pass/fail per job, and posts a one-screen digest to Discord (and SMS if enabled). Useful for catching jobs that pass but should have flagged — e.g. a backup that completed but produced 0 bytes."
    },
    {
      "q": "Can I install it unattended for CI / automation?",
      "a": "Yes — pass channel config as env vars and run `bash install.sh --yes`. Example: `CRONALARM_DISCORD_WEBHOOK=\"https://...\" CRONALARM_SMS_PHONE=\"5551234567\" bash install.sh --yes`. The script writes config to ~/.cronalarm/env without prompting."
    },
    {
      "q": "Where do failure reports live?",
      "a": "Three places: structured logs at ~/.cronalarm/logs/YYYY-MM-DD.log (one per day), failure inbox files at ~/.cronalarm/inbox/ (one per failure, always written even if all channels are unconfigured), and whatever notification channels you configured. Local file drop is the durability anchor."
    },
    {
      "q": "Does it phone home?",
      "a": "No telemetry. Outbound calls only fire when a channel is configured AND a job fails or the daily report runs."
    }
  ],

